Here's a complete example of a C# MCP server wrapping a REST API with stdio transport.

---

**Program.cs** — host setup with stdio transport and DI:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: stdio uses stdout for JSON-RPC — logs must go to stderr
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient("api", client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com");
});

builder.Services
    .AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

**PostTools.cs** — tool class wrapping the REST API:

```csharp
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Net.Http.Json;
using System.Text.Json.Serialization;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

[McpServerToolType]
public class PostTools(IHttpClientFactory httpFactory, ILogger<PostTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get a blog post by its numeric ID.")]
    public async Task<string> GetPost(
        [Description("The post ID (1-100)")] int postId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching post {PostId}", postId);
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("api");
        var post = await client.GetFromJsonAsync<Post>(
            $"/posts/{postId}", cancellationToken);
        return $"Title: {post!.Title}\n\n{post.Body}";
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Search posts by user ID.")]
    public async Task<string> GetPostsByUser(
        [Description("The user ID to filter by")] int userId,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("api");
        var posts = await client.GetFromJsonAsync<Post[]>(
            $"/posts?userId={userId}", cancellationToken);
        return string.Join("\n", posts!.Select(p => $"[{p.Id}] {p.Title}"));
    }
}

public record Post(
    [property: JsonPropertyName("id")] int Id,
    [property: JsonPropertyName("userId")] int UserId,
    [property: JsonPropertyName("title")] string Title,
    [property: JsonPropertyName("body")] string Body);
```

---

### How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK has **two injection styles**:

| Style | How it works |
|-------|-------------|
| **Constructor injection** (non-static class) | The class is resolved from the DI container. Services like `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>` go in the primary constructor. This is the example above. |
| **Method parameter injection** (static class) | DI services appear as method parameters alongside tool inputs. The SDK distinguishes them automatically — DI services are **never** exposed in the tool schema. |

**What gets auto-injected** (never appears in schema):
- `CancellationToken` — cooperative cancellation
- `IMcpServer` — server instance for notifications/logging  
- `IProgress<ProgressNotificationValue>` — progress reporting
- Any service registered in the DI container (e.g., `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`)

**What appears in the tool schema** (visible to LLMs):
- Parameters with `[Description("...")]` attributes — these are the tool's inputs

The key rule: **every tool method and every user-facing parameter must have a `[Description]`** attribute, or the LLM won't know when/how to use the tool.
